,"literature","law","social_reform"],"notable_blurb":"Latin lexicographer behind Harper's Latin Dictionary","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethan_Allen_Andrews_(lexicographer)","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"literature","header":"His Latin dictionary became Harper's Latin Dictionary","body":"Andrews published a Latin-English lexicon in 1850 that was revised into Harper's Latin Dictionary, a standard reference well into the twentieth century. Yale awarded him a doctorate in 1848 for his classical scholarship.","number":1},{"category":"education","header":"He taught ancient languages across the country","body":"A Yale graduate of 1810, Andrews practiced law before turning to teaching, holding a professorship of ancient languages at the University of North Carolina and later running schools in New Haven and Boston. He co-wrote a widely used Latin grammar.","number":2},{"category":"law","header":"He sat as legislator, magistrate, and judge","body":"Back in New Britain, Andrews served as a Whig state legislator, a magistrate, and a judge of probate. He kept at his books to the end, dying in 1858 in the midst of his literary labors.","number":3},{"category":"social_reform","header":"His book on slavery drew abolitionist fire","body":"In 1836 Andrews published a study of slavery and the domestic slave trade that The Liberator attacked as a pro-slavery apologia. The work set the scholar awkwardly against the rising antislavery tide of his native Connecticut.","number":4}],"cross_connections":[],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","school_name":"Yale College","type":"university","degree":"B.A.","graduation_year":1810,"notable":true,"institution_blurb":"Graduated Yale 1810; Yale conferred LL.D. 1848 for Latin scholarship."},{"institution_id":"INST022","school_name":"Yale University","type":"university","degree":"LL.D.","graduation_year":1848,"notable":true,"institution_blurb":"Yale conferred LL.D. 1848 for eminence as Latin